&gt; &gt; When your tests only use the public interfaces they usually don&#39;t
&gt; &gt; break
&gt; &gt; during refactoring. They might become redundant, i.e. worthless, when
&gt; &gt; you
&gt; &gt; test a special case which is no special case in the new refactored
&gt; &gt; implementation any more.
&gt;
&gt; Redundant is *not* worthless in this case! If you refactor again, later,
the
&gt; redundant tests may no longer be redundant. That was the thrust of this
second
&gt; point: it&#39;s not enough to cover the current implementation, one must try
to
&gt; cover the problem with one&#39;s tests. The idea is to have a set of tests
that
&gt; would indicate whether any reasonable implementation of the feature would
work.
&gt; I&#39;m not saying that this is easy.

Test theory says that&#39;s not possible in the general case. Binder [Binder00]
calls that the antiextensionality axiom. He states &quot;that a test suite that
covers one implementation of a specification does not necessarily cover a
different implementation of the same specification&quot;.

I interpret &quot;not necessarily&quot; as &quot;there&#39;s no such thing in the general
case&quot;. One short example which is hopefully obvious enough this time.
Consider a function for sorting an array of String objects:

public String[] sort(String[] unsortedStrings) {
    if (unsortedStrings.length &lt; 20) {
        return bubblesort(unsortedStrings);
    } else {
        return quicksort(unsortedStrings);
    }
}

To have a test case with reasonable coverage you have to do (at least) two
tests:
- Sorting 19 (or less) String objects
- Sorting 20 (or more) String objects

Now performance considerations lead to a changed implementaion:

public String[] sort(String[] unsortedStrings) {
    if (unsortedStrings.length &lt; 20) {
        return bubblesort(unsortedStrings);
    } else if (unsortedStrings.length &lt; 100) {
        return quicksort(unsortedStrings);
    } else {
        return mergesort(unsortedStrings);
    }
}

For good coverage you now have to add another test case: sort 100 or more
String objects. How big is the test suite which covers any reasonable
implementation? Do you have to test any number of String objects from 0 to
whatever? BTW, the AE axiom is one (of many) reasons why functional
(specification-based) tests alone are not enough. IMO we need
implementation-aware tests to go beyond a certain level of quality.

Johannes

